Rating: 2
I used half Rome Beauty, half Idared in my pie (both apples are known to hold their shape and are not very juicy), and followed the filling recipe exactly as written. I was shocked to find a pool of apple soup when I cut the pie approximately 1/2 hour after removing it from the oven. I started looking at other recipes to determine what had gone wrong. My Joy of Cooking has almost exactly the same recipe, with just two differences: 1.) increase the flour to 4 tbsp., and 2.) allow the pie to cool completely for at least 3-4 hours before cutting and serving. JofC specifically states that the lengthy cooling period is necessary to allow the filling to set up properly. It suggests that if you want to eat this pie warm, you should *rewarm* it in a 350 degree oven only after it has cooled completely. I wish that I had consulted my Joy before trying this apple pie!

Rating: 0
to other bakers: getting "apple soup" is normal. Mcintosh apples release lots of liquid. I do my pie differently - I precook the apple filling on the stove for 15 minutes - drain the liquid - cool - then add it to the crust to bake for another 20 minutes. Less soup. Of course, I like my pie filling soft not crunchy like some people - so this process may not be for you.

